The assassination of Caesar in 44 brought Cicero again into public life. He had no part in that act of political folly, but he fully justified it. He and the conspirators seem to have imagined that Caesar was a simple obstacle to the ordinary working of the government, and that, if he were removed, all would go on as before. The terrible years of war and proscription which followed showed how frightful was their mistake. In fact, the great mistake of Cicero's life, arising from his love for the institutione ot* his country, was his failure to perceive that their vitality was gone, and that something must be substituted in ,their place Õæ but his sincerity he attested by the work and the sacrifice oi his life.
